post_text: Kirtland Elementary School's First Responders Vehicle Parade #hornetpride
text: Kirtland Elementary School's First Responders Vehicle Parade #hornetpride

post_text:
In honor of Patriot Day and appreciation for all that local law enforcement officers do to keep the school district’s communities safe, Kirtland Elementary School students and staff participated in a First Responders Vehicle Parade on Friday, September 11.

Socially distanced and wearing masks, students and staff lined the driveway and sidewalk behind the school. They continued along the inside of the fence around the perimeter of the playground. As the safety forces’ vehicle parade made its way through the route, the school honored these local heroes by waving, cheering, clapping and holding signs. Wearing red, white and blue, the students enjoyed saluting the officers and watching them…

post_text: Kirtland Local Schools needed to bring in old single desks to maximize the space in its classrooms to accommodate the 82% of students returning to school on September 8. On August 25, 700 desks were brought to the campus and loaded into classrooms in one day. To make this happen, Kirtland resident Jeff Collins donated the moving trucks and a lot of workers from his company, Moving Ahead Service. They dedicated their entire day to helping the district. Our Kirtland custodial staff was absolutely inspiring. "What took place on our campus is a great example of what makes me proud to be a Kirtlander," said Superintendent Chad VanArnhem, Kirtland Local Schools. "Everyone worked tirelessly… More

An email was sent to families that included our district's reopening plans. We are asking parents to select a choice through Final Forms as to how their child will attend school (with busing, without busing, remote learning). Please fill this form out by August 7. The link to the form is on page 25 of the Return to School Plan.

Then plan, along with a video explanation by Mr. VanArnhem can be found here: http://www.kirtlandschools.org/COVID-19Updates.aspx

There is also a Q&A that will continually be updated with the answers to the questions we receive. Please use this form to submit questions: https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScovxYQmhW6TOaFhD6Ba6C5vB0z7Svn70HCuxTPtgSaplKGiw/viewform

From Kirtland Elementary School Principal Chad VanArnhem:

Our new adaptive reading program called Lexia has been uploaded for all students! The program will teach and reinforce a variety of reading and phonics skills. I highly encourage you to have your child start using this program. It will fill in any gaps or weaker areas in reading/phonics while pushing your child further ahead in areas of strength. One very important note, on the initial assessment that your child takes, do NOT help him or her with the answers but monitor and encourage him or her to do his or her best. This will put your child at the appropriate educational level for the program to work properly.

To access the program,…

KIRTLAND PUBLIC LIBRARY SUMMER READING

Summer Reading at the Kirtland Public Library will begin June 1 and end July 18. Use the READSquared app to log your reading. Kids will sign up for either the Pre-K, Child, or Teen program, and log minutes. Adults will sign up for the Adult program, and count books. Earn points and virtual badges for reading whatever you are interested in.

Attend virtual programs, starting with the live Jester Jim juggling show at 11am on Monday, June 1 at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=E6XjAEJJFqY&feature=youtu.be.

A Kirtland High School teacher and student are putting their sewing skills to work in creating homemade face masks for friends and family.

KHS English teacher Jennifer Berry, whose husband Rich is a family medicine doctor with Lake Health Physician Group Lake County Family Practice, initially made a mask out of ducky material for him. After a few weeks of mostly telemedicine visits, Dr. Berry was returning to inpatient visits and had to wear a cloth mast in and out of the building, and a surgical mask in the practice.

“I had the ducky material form a baby blanket I never managed to make,” Jennifer Berry said. “As Rich has many pediatric patients, he was pretty excited about the fabric.

“I…

Wear a cloth face covering to slow the spread of coronavirus. Growing evidence suggests the virus can spread:
• Before people show symptoms (pre-symptomatic) and
• From people who have the virus but never show symptoms (asymptomatic).

post_text: Once again, Kirtland High School has been named as one of the best high schools in the country by U.S. News and World Report. KHS is ranked #102 in Ohio high schools and #26 in Cleveland. Nearly 18,000 schools nationwide were ranked this year. Many thanks to our dedicated teachers, staff and school families for their commitment to excellence in education at Kirtland Local Schools.
text: Once again, Kirtland High School has been named as one of the best high schools in the country by U.S. News and World Report. KHS is ranked #102 in Ohio high schools and #26 in Cleveland. Nearly 18,000 schools nationwide were ranked this year. Many thanks to our dedicated teachers, staff and school families for their commitment to excellence in education at Kirtland Local Schools.

post_text: KHS junior TJ Green is taking up a collection for “End 68 Hours of Hunger Lake County.” This organization is for families that need food in Lake County. A food donation box will be placed in front of the entrance to Kirtland High School and will be open to donations at all times. The food will be picked up every night and delivered to the collection facility in Painesville every Thursday. They are specifically looking for Mac'n'Cheese, soup, canned vegetables and fruit, applesauce, Ramen, canned pasta, oatmeal, cereal, and granola bars.

post_text: Kirtland Elementary School's fourth-grade students went on a "word search" for the spelling pattern of consonant "le" words, then shared on Seesaw. Not only did students say their words, but they also had them on display. Some examples of this spelling pattern were turtle, needle, apple, puzzle, table, Skittle and purple!

post_text: Kirtland Elementary School teacher Alysha Needham has morning Zoom meetings everyday with her first-grade class. Students provided a "tour" of their home school environments and sent pictures on Seesaw, where Needham assigns work and provides feedback to her students. They also take spelling tests, practice phonics skills and work on STEAM projects. Her students also are working on realistic fiction books each day and will take video of themselves reading it.

post_text: Kirtland Elementary School art students took a virtual field trip to the Cleveland Museum of Art recently. Rose Caruso's students visited the virtual art gallery available on the CMA's website and found a work of art that stood out to them. they submitted the artist's name, date of create and name of the artwork they chose, along with a short description of why this piece spoke to them. They also had the option of re-creating their own version of a piece of art.

The Ohio "At Home Learning" initiative includes a full schedule of daily programming geared toward PK-12 students ooh Ohio PBS channels in every community. Daily weekday programming will range from the PBS Kids series "Peg+Cat" and "Cyberchase" focused on math skills for early elementary, to "NOVA" and "American Experience" programming for older students.

The educational teams at each station will provide additional teacher resources related to the new programming schedule. Teachers and students also have access to PBS Learning Media to support the programming with free online resources at https://pbslearningmedia.org.

This afternoon Gov. Mike DeWine extended his order on school closures through the end of the month. Schools will remain closed through May 1, at which time state government and health officials will reevaluate. This means that distance learning for Kirtland Local Schools will continue through that time.

We also wanted to remind our families with children in the Free and Reduced lunch program that we are offering grab-and-go style breakfasts and lunches. You can pick up those meals Mondays and Wednesdays between 8:30 and 10am at the entrance behind the high school cafeteria. If that window of time does not work for your family, please contact Food Service Director Ginni Vacarro at…

shared_text:
City of Kirtland is at Kirtland Community Center.
March 20 at 5:27 PM · Kirtland, OH ·

Kirtland CARES 🌷 NEEDS COLLECTION

Due to the current crisis in our area, the City of Kirtland has established KIRTLAND CARES. The primary objective of this effort is to make sure members of our community do not go without, during this time.
🗓 Starting Monday, March 23, the Kirtland Community Center, located at 7900 Euclid-Chardon Road, will be a drop-off point, weekdays, from 10:00AM - 2:00 PM for nonperishable food, household items, and basic first aid supplies.
🔴 Those wishing to donate to the KIRTLAND CARES cause, are asked to drop off supplies at the front entryway of the Community Center.
⚪️ Please bring the items in boxes, bags, or containers that you do not want back. As needs arise, the items will be distributed to residents by city personnel and healthy volunteers from the community.
🔵 The building will not be open to the public but support staff will be on site to retrieve the items as they are dropped off.
📧 Reach out to Kirtlandcares@KirtlandOhio.com for more information.
🌷Be well! Thank you!

The City of Kirtland

post_text:
Kindergarten registration for the 2020-2021 school year will be on May 15. Parents of incoming kindergarten students can find a variety of information on our website at http://www.kirtlandschools.org/KindergartenOrientation.aspx.

You will find:
1. A sign-up for a presentation, question and answer period and tour of the building. It will be offered on three different days for incoming kindergarten parents/guardians. This is for adults only.
2. Available times for registration on May 15. You will bring your child during your selected time.
3. The necessary forms “Final Forms” that need to be completed prior to registration.
4. All other printable forms and information.

If you have questions or need help, please feel free to reach out to the KES office at 440.256.3344 ext. 2000.
